            <tr>
             <td class="statText" colspan="2">
              <h3>
               Examples
              </h3>
             </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
             <td align="center" class="statText" nowrap="true">
              0)
             </td>
             <td class="statText">
             </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
             <td class="statText">
             </td>
             <td class="statText">
              <table>
               <tr>
                <td class="statText">
                 <table>
                  <tr>
                   <td class="statText">
                    <pre>{"99 01","99   001"}</pre>
                   </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                   <td class="statText">
                    <pre>{1000000,0}</pre>
                   </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                   <td class="statText">
                    <pre>2</pre>
                   </td>
                  </tr>
                 </table>
                </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                <td class="statText">
                 <pre>Returns: { 990000,  10000 }</pre>
                </td>
               </tr>
               <tr>
                <td class="statText">
                 <table>
                  <tr>
                   <td class="statText" colspan="2">
                    <p>
                     At the start there are 1,000,000 people in major 0, and none in major 1.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                     During the first year, 1% of the people in major 0 switch to major 1.  Thus, after one year there are 990,000 people in major 0 and 10,000 people in major 1.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                     During the second year, 1% of the people in major 0 (0.01 * 990,000 = 9900)
switch to major 1.  At the same time, 99 percent of the people in major 1
switch to major 0 (0.99 * 10,000 = 9900).  Since the same number of people
switch from major 0 to major 1 as switch from major 1 to major 0, there is no
net change in the number of people in the two majors.  Thus, after two years
(and after any number of years greater than two), there are 990,000 people in
major 0, and 10,000 people in major 1.
                    </p>
                   </td>
                  </tr>
                 </table>
                </td>
               </tr>
              </table>
             </td>
            </tr>
